Solution:
We want to minimize the product $6 \cdot 7 \cdot 8 \cdot 9 = 3^2 \cdot 2 \cdot 7^2.$  We can put 6 and 7 in the top row, and 8 and 9 in the bottom row.  Then we put the smaller of 8 and 9 in the left column, and the larger in the right column.  This gives us the arrangement below.

[asy]
draw((0,.5)--(10,.5),linewidth(1));
draw((4,1)--(6,1)--(6,3)--(4,3)--(4,1),linewidth(1));
draw((7,1)--(9,1)--(9,3)--(7,3)--(7,1),linewidth(1));
draw((7,4)--(9,4)--(9,6)--(7,6)--(7,4),linewidth(1));
draw((4,4)--(6,4)--(6,6)--(4,6)--(4,4),linewidth(1));
draw((1,3)--(2,4),linewidth(1));
draw((1,4)--(2,3),linewidth(1));
label("6",(5,2));
label("7",(9,2));
label("8",(5,5));
label("9",(9,5));
[/asy]

Therefore, the smallest possible product is $6 \cdot 7 \cdot 8 \cdot 9 = \boxed{3024}.$

